<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910918-0051</DOCNO><DOCID>910918-0051.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Ackerley Communications Inc.:   Bank Agreement Is Reached   To Restructure Senior Debt</HL><DATE>09/18/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   AK</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><NS>BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)FINANCING AGREEMENTS (FNC)RESTRUCTURINGS, RECAPITALIZATION (RCN)ACQUISITIONS andamp; MERGERS, TAKEOVERS, BOARD BATTLES (TNM)</NS><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)WASHINGTON (WA)</RE><LP>   Ackerley Communications Inc., Seattle, said it reached anagreement in principle with First National Bank of Chicago torestructure its senior debt, including a reduction in thecurrent portion of the indebtedness to $15.4 million from$246.1 million.   Ackerley, a media concern that also owns the SeattleSuperSonics basketball team, defaulted on the debt last June,prompting most of its senior debt to be declared current. Thecompany, which owns several TV and radio stations, has beenhit hard by the recession and declining advertising. It saidproposed terms of the new arrangement include waivers on allcurrent defaults as well as less stringent financialcovenants.</LP><TEXT>   As part of the restructuring, Ackerley also said it agreedto sell a number of assets, including a Seattle site where ithad once hoped to build a new $100 million sports arena; thearena project was scrapped in June because of financingtroubles and other problems.   Ackerley said the agreement is subject to a definitiveagreement by Oct. 31.</TEXT></DOC>